## K-means data sampling


income_index <- createDataPartition(income$income_above_50k, p = 0.80, list = FALSE)
train <- income[income_index, ]
test <- income[-income_index, ]

train <- train%>%
  select(-income_above_50k)
### Elbow Method- Optimal Number of Clusters```{r}
set.seed(503)

# function to compute total within-cluster sum of square 
wss <- function(k) {
  kmeans(train, k, nstart = 10 )$tot.withinss
}

# Compute and plot wss for k = 1 to k = 15
k.values <- 1:15

# extract wss for 2-15 clusters
wss_values <- map_dbl(k.values, wss)

plot(k.values, wss_values,
       type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
       xlab="Number of clusters K",
       ylab="Total within-clusters sum of squares")

## # A tibble: 1  4
##     totss tot.withinss betweenss  iter
##     <dbl>        <dbl>     <dbl> <int>
## 1 4.02e14      5.87e13   3.43e14     2
kclusts<-tibble(k=1:9)%>% mutate( kclust=map(k,~kmeans(train,.x)), 
                                  glanced=map(kclust,glance), 
                                  augmented=map(kclust,augment,train) )

assignments<-kclusts%>% unnest(augmented)
ggplot(assignments,aes(fnlwgt,age))+ 
  geom_point(aes(color=.cluster),alpha=0.3)+ 
  facet_wrap(~k)

clusterings<-kclusts%>% unnest(glanced,.drop=TRUE) 

ggplot(clusterings,aes(k,tot.withinss))+ geom_line()
